WinRM is a component of the Windows hardware management feature that manages server hardware remotely and locally.
 Technology: Remote management technology by Microsoft.
 Protocol: Uses WS-Management Protocol.
 Service Name: The name of the WinRM service is WinRM.
 WS-Management Protocol
 A SOAP-based protocol used for remote management.
 Ports:
 5985 HTTP (Same network)
 5986 HTTPS (Different network)
 Key Components & Features
1. WinRM Scripting API:
 Used by scripts and applications to communicate remotely using WS-Management Protocol.
 Works as a layer above the WS-Man protocol.
 Helps manage local and remote systems (obtain system data, manage resources, automate admin tasks).
2. WinRM.cmd (WinRM.vbs):
 Command-line management tool for WinRM.
 Enables admins to get or manage resources.
3. WinRS.exe:
 Command-line tool for remote command execution.
 Uses WS-Management protocol.
 WinRM Listener
 service that listens for remote management requests using the WS-Management protocol.
 Receives and sends management messages between computers.
 Can use HTTP and HTTPS.
 Authentication Methods in WinRM
1. Kerberos: Default mode of authentication when the client is in the domain.
2. Negotiate:
 Default mode of authentication when the client is not in the domain.
 Automatically decides whether to use Kerberos or NTLM.
 If Kerberos is unavailable, it falls back to NTLM.
3. Basic Authentication:
 Username and password are sent to the server.
 Less secure compared to Kerberos.
 Disabled by default in WinRM.
 Recommended to use only with HTTPS.
4. Client Certificate Based Authentication:
 Needs to be enabled on both client and server using the WinRM command-line tool.
 Maximum certificate size supported by WinRM is 16 KB.
 Event Forwarding
Used to collect Windows event logs from remote computers to a central server.
 Types
Collector Initiated (PULL): Collector server contacts client computers and pulls events from them. (Not preferred because it is not scalable).
Source Initiated (PUSH): Collector will wait for incoming connections from the clients. (Requires policy deployment to clients to point to the collector).
Common Requirements
Subscription on the Collector Server.
WinRM service enabled on both Client and Server.
The account used to create the subscription needs "Event Log Readers" permissions.
Service Name: Windows Event Collector service name is Wecsvc.

MMC (Microsoft Management Console)
Admin console for Windows management.
Service name: mmc.exe.
Examples of MMC Snap-ins: Event Viewer, Disk Management, Group Policy, Shared Folders.
Task Scheduler
Windows feature used to automate tasks based on time, events, or system actions.
 Service Name: Schedule.
 Main Components of TS
1.Triggers: Decide when a task will start (e.g., At logon, At startup).
2.Actions: Define what work the task will perform (e.g., Run a program, execute script).
3.Principals: Define the user/security account under which the task runs (e.g., Admin, System Account).
4.Settings: Control how the task behaves (e.g., Stop task after certain time, restart if failed).
 Types of Triggers
 Time-based: Runs tasks at a scheduled time.
 Event-based: Runs task when a specific event occurs.
 Multiple Triggers:more than one trigger (e.g., Run at startup AND every Sunday at 9 PM).
 MSI (Windows Installer)
Windows installation and deployment technology.
 Features: Transactional installation, Self-healing, Patch management, Custom installation.
 Service Name: msiserver
 Display Name: Windows Installer
 Executable: msiexec.exe
 Path: C:\Windows\System32
 File Extensions
 .msi Installer database
 .msm Merge module
 .msp Patch
 .mst Transform
 Requirement for MSI Package: Certificate (.pfx)
 WinRM Commands
1. winrm quickconfig: To configure WinRM for the first time.
2. winrm e winrm/config/listener: To check listeners.
3. winrm get winrm/config: To view the configuration.
4. winrm set winrm/config/client/auth @{Basic="true"}: Used to change or set authentication types.
